  "prompt": "What has replaced CGI (common gateway interface) in today's web?",
  "response": "In today's web, CGI (Common Gateway Interface) has been largely replaced by more modern and efficient technologies. Some of the key replacements include:\n\n1. **Server-side scripting languages and frameworks:**\n   - **PHP, Python (Django, Flask), Ruby (Ruby on Rails), and Node.js (Express.js):** These languages and frameworks offer more robust, efficient, and scalable ways to handle server-side logic and generate dynamic content.\n\n2. **Application Servers:**\n   - **Java (Jakarta EE, formerly Java EE), .NET:** Application servers provide a more comprehensive environment for running applications, managing resources, and scaling operations.\n\n3. **API-driven architectures:**\n   - **RESTful APIs, GraphQL:** These technologies allow for better separation of concerns, enabling more flexible and scalable interactions between the client and server.\n\n4. **Serverless Architectures:**\n   - **AWS Lambda, Google Cloud Functions, Azure Functions:** Serverless computing allows developers to run code without managing servers, offering a more cost-effective and scalable solution.\n\n5. **Web Application Frameworks:**\n   - **ASP.NET, Laravel, Spring Boot:** These frameworks provide a structured approach to building web applications, often with built-in features for handling HTTP requests, managing sessions, and more.\n\nCGI, while still in use in some legacy systems, is considered outdated due to its inefficiencies and limitations compared to these modern alternatives.",
